Mathematical Certification of Non-Thermal Plasma-Catalytic Systems for Trace VOC Oxidation in Low-Pressure CO₂ Martian Habitats: Existence, Uniqueness, Reduced-Order Modeling, and Certified Control Algorithms

Author

Ouadi Maakoul

Abstract

This thesis develops a complete mathematical framework for the certification of non-thermal plasma (NTP) catalytic reactors designed to oxidize trace volatile organic compounds (VOCs) under Martian ambient conditions (600 Pa CO₂, 295 K). The work addresses a critical gap: existing empirical approaches cannot guarantee safety (e.g., ozone concentration below 0.05 ppm), stability, or performance under uncertainty, preventing flight certification for human spaceflight.

We first derive a 0‑dimensional master equation for 35 chemical species (electrons, CO₂, CO, O, O₂, O₃, H₂O, OH, H, HCHO, C₆H₆, NH₃, and intermediates) with 200 reactions, coupled to a parametric electron energy distribution function (EEDF) computed via BOLSIG+. At 600 Pa, the electron Knudsen number is \mathrm{Kn}_e \approx 0.3–1.0, invalidating local field approximations. We introduce a first‑order non‑local correction T_e^{\mathrm{eff}} = T_e^{\mathrm{local}}(1 + \alpha\,\mathrm{Kn}_e) and prove a rigorous error bound \|\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{c}_{\mathrm{local}}\|_2 \leq C\,\mathrm{Kn}_e over the residence time.

For the resulting stiff ODE system, we prove global existence and uniqueness of non‑negative bounded solutions using quasi‑positivity, atomic conservation laws, and a logarithmic Lyapunov functional. A reduced‑order model (ROM) is constructed via proper orthogonal decomposition (POD) of an ensemble of 2000 high‑fidelity simulations, with a certified error bound of 5% and evaluation time under 10 ms.

We build Gaussian process (GP) surrogates with a Matérn‑7/2 kernel and multiplicative heteroscedastic noise to predict VOC removal efficiency, ozone and NOₓ concentrations, and power consumption. Posterior consistency is proven, and credible intervals achieve 95% nominal coverage on hold‑out synthetic data.

A reinforcement learning (RL) controller with a control‑Lyapunov barrier function, constructed via sum‑of‑squares (SOS) optimization, guarantees forward invariance of the safe set (O₃ < 0.05 ppm, NOₓ < 0.1 ppm). The policy satisfies \dot{V} \leq -\kappa V with \kappa = 0.12\,\text{s}^{-1}, and cumulative regret is bounded by O(\sqrt{T\gamma_T}).

Bayesian optimization under stochastic constraints (flow uniformity modeled as a GP) is developed (SAFE‑BO), with a convergence proof showing simple regret O(\sqrt{\gamma_T/T}). This yields an optimal reactor design (electrode gap, dielectric thickness, catalyst loading, type, packing density) with a certified lifetime exceeding 10,000 h.

Finally, we design a computer‑vision monitoring algorithm based on wavelet transform of synthetic emission intensity. A Hoeffding‑type bound guarantees false‑positive rates below 5% under bounded dust noise, and conformal prediction sets provide distribution‑free 95% coverage for discharge regime classification (streamer, glow, fouled).

All algorithms are implemented in open‑source libraries (ROM, hetGP, RL‑SOS, SAFE‑BO, wavelet‑CNN), formally verified using Isabelle/HOL and interval arithmetic, and cross‑validated against experimental data from the literature (Kozák et al. 2021). The framework reaches Algorithmic Readiness Level 5, ready for integration with hardware partners.

