2.2 Mathematical Model of Plasma Chemistry at 600 Pa

2.2.1 Species and Reactions

We consider 35 chemical species relevant to CO₂/VOC mixtures in a dielectric barrier discharge (DBD) reactor:

· Electrons: e⁻
· Neutral molecules: CO₂, CO, O₂, O₃, H₂O, H₂, HCHO, C₆H₆, NH₃, N₂ (trace), CH₃CHO, etc.
· Radicals and excited states: O(³P), O(¹D), OH, H, HO₂, CO₂(vib), CO(vib), N, NH, etc.
· Ions: CO₂⁺, O₂⁺, O⁻, O₂⁻, H₃O⁺, etc.

The reaction mechanism includes 200 reactions: electron impact ionization, attachment, dissociation, excitation; ion‑neutral reactions; neutral‑neutral reactions; radical recombination; VOC oxidation pathways. Cross‑sections and rate coefficients will be taken from the LXCat database and literature (Kozák et al. 2021; Snoeckx & Bogaerts 2017).

2.2.2 Zero‑Dimensional Master Equation

In a well‑mixed, spatially homogeneous plasma (residence time τ ≈ 0.05–0.2 s, diffusion time ≫ τ), the species concentrations c_i(t) (i = 1,…,35) evolve according to:

\frac{dc_i}{dt} = \sum_{r=1}^{200} \nu_{ir} \, k_r(T_e, T_g) \prod_{j=1}^{35} c_j^{\alpha_{jr}}, \qquad i = 1,\dots,35,
\tag{2.1}

where \nu_{ir} is the net stoichiometric coefficient of species i in reaction r, \alpha_{jr} the reactant orders, k_r the reaction rate coefficient, T_e the electron temperature (derived from the electron energy distribution function), and T_g the gas temperature (fixed at 295 K in this work). The system is autonomous and defined on the positive orthant \mathbb{R}_+^{35}.

The electron temperature T_e is not a separate dynamic variable but is determined from the reduced electric field E/N (where N is the total number density) via the electron energy distribution function (EEDF). At low pressure, the EEDF is obtained by solving the homogeneous Boltzmann equation using BOLSIG+ (Hagelaar & Pitchford 2005). The input is the reduced field E/N (100–400 Td) and the gas composition. The output is the mean electron energy \langle \varepsilon \rangle and the rate coefficients k_r(T_e). For computational efficiency in the ROM and GP surrogate, we will parameterize T_e as a function of E/N and the mixture composition using a neural network trained on BOLSIG+ data.

2.2.3 Transition‑Regime Correction (Knudsen Number Effect)

At 600 Pa and a typical electrode gap of 3–5 mm, the electron mean free path \lambda_{\text{mfp}} is 1–10 mm, giving \text{Kn}_e = \lambda_{\text{mfp}} / d_{\text{gap}} \approx 0.3–1.0. This invalidates the local field approximation (LFA) and the two‑term spherical harmonics expansion used in standard BOLSIG+. To correct for non‑local kinetic effects, we introduce an effective electron temperature:

T_e^{\text{eff}} = T_e^{\text{local}} \bigl(1 + \alpha \,\text{Kn}_e\bigr),
\tag{2.2}

where T_e^{\text{local}} is the value from the local Boltzmann solver, \text{Kn}_e = \lambda_{\text{mfp}} / d_{\text{gap}}, and \alpha is a closure constant determined by a first‑order Chapman–Enskog expansion of the full phase‑space Boltzmann equation. The error incurred by this approximation is bounded by:

\|\mathbf{c}(t) - \mathbf{c}_{\text{local}}(t)\|_2 \leq C \,\text{Kn}_e \qquad \forall t \in [0, \tau_{\text{res}}],
\tag{2.3}

with C depending on the Lipschitz constants of the reaction rates and the residence time. This bound is derived in Appendix A.3.

Design decision: We will fix \alpha = 0.35 based on a least‑squares fit to a set of high‑fidelity particle‑in‑cell simulations from the literature (Turner 2019). For the remainder of this work, all rate coefficients will be computed using T_e^{\text{eff}}.

