2.3 Existence, Uniqueness, and Boundedness of Solutions

We rewrite (2.1) in vector form:

\frac{d\mathbf{c}}{dt} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{c}), \quad \mathbf{c}(0) = \mathbf{c}_0 \in \mathbb{R}_+^{35},
\tag{2.4}

where \mathbf{f} = (f_1,\dots,f_{35}) is a polynomial (or rational) function due to mass‑action kinetics. The following properties hold by construction of the reaction mechanism:

1. Quasi‑positivity: For each i, if c_i = 0 then f_i(\mathbf{c}) \ge 0. This ensures that trajectories cannot leave the positive orthant.
2. Conservation of atoms: There exist positive constants A_j (for C, H, O, N) such that \sum_{i=1}^{35} A_{ji} c_i(t) is constant in time.
3. Boundedness of reaction rates: For any compact set K \subset \mathbb{R}_+^{35}, there exists L_K such that \|\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{c}) - \mathbf{f}(\tilde{\mathbf{c}})\| \le L_K \|\mathbf{c} - \tilde{\mathbf{c}}\| (local Lipschitz).

Theorem 2.1 (Global existence and uniqueness). For any initial condition \mathbf{c}_0 \in \mathbb{R}_+^{35} with finite total atomic mass, there exists a unique solution \mathbf{c}(t) \in \mathbb{R}_+^{35} for all t \ge 0, and the solution remains bounded: there exists M > 0 (depending on \mathbf{c}_0) such that \|\mathbf{c}(t)\|_1 \le M for all t \in [0, \tau_{\text{res}}].

Proof sketch.
Local existence and uniqueness follow from the Picard–Lindelöf theorem because \mathbf{f} is locally Lipschitz on the open set \mathbb{R}_+^{35}. Quasi‑positivity implies that if a trajectory reaches the boundary c_i = 0, it cannot cross into negative values; hence the solution remains in \mathbb{R}_+^{35} as long as it exists. To prevent finite‑time blow‑up, consider the total mass M(t) = \sum_i m_i c_i(t) (with molecular masses m_i). Atomic conservation gives M(t) = M(0). Moreover, the logarithmic Lyapunov functional L(\mathbf{c}) = \sum_i c_i \log c_i satisfies:

\frac{dL}{dt} = \sum_i f_i(\mathbf{c}) (1 + \log c_i).

Using the structure of the reaction rates (detailed balance and recombination), one can show \dot{L} \le K for some constant K on the set where M(t) is bounded. Therefore L(t) grows at most linearly, which implies that no concentration can become infinite in finite time. A standard continuation argument extends the solution to all t \ge 0. For the full proof, see Appendix A.1. ∎

Corollary 2.1 (Invariant region). The set \mathcal{R} = \{\mathbf{c} \in \mathbb{R}_+^{35} : \sum_i A_{ji} c_i = \text{const}, \, \|\mathbf{c}\|_1 \le M\} is positively invariant.

