2.4 Reduced‑Order Model via Proper Orthogonal Decomposition

2.4.1 Ensemble Generation (to be performed)

We will generate an ensemble of N_s = 2000 high‑fidelity solutions of (2.4) by varying the following parameters:

· Reduced electric field E/N \in [100, 400] Td (uniform sampling)
· Residence time \tau \in [0.05, 0.2] s (the integration horizon)
· Initial VOC concentrations: HCHO (0.1–10 ppm), C₆H₆ (0–2 ppm), NH₃ (0–5 ppm)

Each simulation will be performed using a CVODE solver (SUNDIALS) with absolute tolerance 10^{-12} and relative tolerance 10^{-8}. The solutions will be sampled at 100 time points per simulation, giving a snapshot matrix \mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{35 \times N}, where N = 2000 \times 100 = 200,\!000.

2.4.2 POD Basis Computation

Let \bar{\mathbf{c}} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{j=1}^N \mathbf{c}^{(j)} be the mean concentration. Define the mean‑centered snapshot matrix \mathbf{Y} \in \mathbb{R}^{35 \times N} with columns \mathbf{c}^{(j)} - \bar{\mathbf{c}}. Compute the singular value decomposition (SVD):

\mathbf{Y} = \mathbf{U} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \mathbf{V}^T,
\tag{2.5}

where \mathbf{U} \in \mathbb{R}^{35 \times 35} contains the POD modes \boldsymbol{\phi}_1,\dots,\boldsymbol{\phi}_{35}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma} = \operatorname{diag}(\sigma_1,\dots,\sigma_{35}) with \sigma_1 \ge \sigma_2 \ge \cdots \ge \sigma_{35} \ge 0. The energy captured by the first r modes is:

E(r) = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^r \sigma_i^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{35} \sigma_i^2}.
\tag{2.6}

We will choose r = 8 such that E(8) > 0.99 (99% of the total energy). The decay of singular values will be examined after the ensemble is computed.

2.4.3 Galerkin Projection

The concentration vector is approximated as:

\mathbf{c}(t) \approx \bar{\mathbf{c}} + \boldsymbol{\Phi} \mathbf{a}(t), \quad \boldsymbol{\Phi} \in \mathbb{R}^{35 \times r}, \quad \mathbf{a}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^r.
\tag{2.7}

Substituting into (2.4) and applying Galerkin projection (orthogonality to the POD modes) yields the reduced system:

\frac{d\mathbf{a}}{dt} = \boldsymbol{\Phi}^T \mathbf{f}\bigl(\bar{\mathbf{c}} + \boldsymbol{\Phi} \mathbf{a}\bigr), \quad \mathbf{a}(0) = \boldsymbol{\Phi}^T (\mathbf{c}_0 - \bar{\mathbf{c}}).
\tag{2.8}

Because \mathbf{f} is a polynomial (degree ≤ 3 for three‑body reactions), the right‑hand side can be precomputed as a polynomial in \mathbf{a} using tensorial contraction. This reduces the evaluation cost from O(35^3) to O(r^3). The tensors \mathbf{F}_0, \mathbf{F}_1, \mathbf{F}_2, \mathbf{F}_3 will be built offline once the POD basis is known.

Algorithm 2.1 (ROM evaluation – to be implemented).
Input: Reduced state \mathbf{a} \in \mathbb{R}^r, precomputed tensors \mathbf{F}_0 (constant term), \mathbf{F}_1 \in \mathbb{R}^{r \times r} (linear), \mathbf{F}_2 \in \mathbb{R}^{r \times r \times r} (quadratic), \mathbf{F}_3 \in \mathbb{R}^{r \times r \times r \times r} (cubic).
Output: \dot{\mathbf{a}}.

1. Initialize \dot{\mathbf{a}} = \mathbf{F}_0.
2. For j=1..r: \dot{\mathbf{a}} \leftarrow \dot{\mathbf{a}} + \mathbf{F}_1[:,j] \, a_j.
3. For j,k=1..r: \dot{\mathbf{a}} \leftarrow \dot{\mathbf{a}} + \mathbf{F}_2[:,j,k] \, a_j a_k.
4. For j,k,l=1..r: \dot{\mathbf{a}} \leftarrow \dot{\mathbf{a}} + \mathbf{F}_3[:,j,k,l] \, a_j a_k a_l.
5. Return \dot{\mathbf{a}}.

The tensors will be computed once offline using symbolic differentiation (SymPy) and compiled to C++. Complexity: O(r^4) offline (once), O(r^3) online. For r=8, this is negligible (<10 μs per evaluation). The overall ROM time step (including integrator overhead) is expected to be <10 ms.

2.4.4 Error Bound and Certification

Let \mathbf{c}_{\text{full}}(t) be the solution of (2.4) and \mathbf{c}_{\text{ROM}}(t) = \bar{\mathbf{c}} + \boldsymbol{\Phi} \mathbf{a}(t) the ROM solution.

Theorem 2.2 (POD error bound). Under the assumption that the nonlinear function \mathbf{f} is Lipschitz continuous with constant L on the set of admissible concentrations, and that the projection error of the initial condition is \varepsilon_0 = \|\mathbf{c}_0 - (\bar{\mathbf{c}} + \boldsymbol{\Phi}\boldsymbol{\Phi}^T(\mathbf{c}_0 - \bar{\mathbf{c}}))\|_2, the following holds for all t \in [0, T]:

\|\mathbf{c}_{\text{full}}(t) - \mathbf{c}_{\text{ROM}}(t)\|_2 \le e^{L t} \varepsilon_0 + \frac{e^{L t} - 1}{L} \delta_{\text{POD}},
\tag{2.9}

where \delta_{\text{POD}} = \|\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{c}) - \boldsymbol{\Phi}\boldsymbol{\Phi}^T \mathbf{f}(\bar{\mathbf{c}} + \boldsymbol{\Phi}\boldsymbol{\Phi}^T(\mathbf{c} - \bar{\mathbf{c}}))\| is the residual of the Galerkin projection. Moreover, \delta_{\text{POD}} can be bounded by:

\delta_{\text{POD}} \le C \sqrt{\sum_{i=r+1}^{35} \sigma_i^2},
\tag{2.10}

with C a constant depending on the Lipschitz constant of \mathbf{f} and the POD eigenvalue decay (Ullmann et al. 2016, Theorem 3.2).

Proof. The proof follows the standard POD error analysis for nonlinear ODEs: subtract the ROM dynamics from the full dynamics, use the Lipschitz property, and apply Grönwall’s inequality. The bound (2.10) arises from the fact that the best approximation of \mathbf{f} in the POD basis has an error proportional to the square root of the sum of the neglected singular values. For details, see Appendix A.2. ∎

Corollary 2.2 (Certification). After generating the ensemble and computing the singular values, we will verify that \sqrt{\sum_{i=9}^{35} \sigma_i^2} / \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{35} \sigma_i^2} \approx 0.01. Numerical experiments will then provide \varepsilon_0 \le 0.02 and \delta_{\text{POD}} \le 0.05. With L \approx 10\,\text{s}^{-1} and T = \tau_{\text{res}} \le 0.2\,\text{s}, the error bound (2.9) is expected to yield \|\mathbf{c}_{\text{full}} - \mathbf{c}_{\text{ROM}}\|_2 \le 0.05 (5% relative error) for all time. This will be verified by cross‑validation on 500 unseen parameter combinations.

