Chapter 4: Reinforcement Learning Control with Lyapunov Stability Guarantees

4.1 Introduction

The reduced-order model (ROM) from Chapter 2 and the Gaussian process (GP) surrogate from Chapter 3 provide fast, uncertainty‑aware predictions of plasma chemistry. However, controlling a plasma reactor for VOC oxidation under time‑varying loads (e.g., sudden release of formaldehyde from 1 ppm to 10 ppm) requires a closed‑loop controller that can adjust the actuator settings (pulse voltage amplitude V_{\text{amp}} and frequency f_{\text{pulse}}) to maintain safety constraints ([\text{O}_3] < 0.05 ppm, [\text{NO}_x] < 0.1 ppm) while maximizing VOC removal efficiency and minimizing power consumption.

Classical PID or model predictive control (MPC) can be used, but they lack formal guarantees of safety under all possible disturbances and model uncertainties. Reinforcement learning (RL) has shown promise for plasma control, but existing methods do not provide Lyapunov stability certificates. In this chapter we design a safe RL controller that combines:

· A control‑Lyapunov barrier function (CLBF) constructed via sum‑of‑squares (SOS) optimization, ensuring forward invariance of the safe set.
· A model predictive control (MPC) layer using the certified ROM for short‑term safety.
· An RL policy (proximal policy optimization, PPO) that learns to optimize long‑term reward while respecting the CLBF constraint.

We prove that the closed‑loop system satisfies \dot{V}(s) \leq -\kappa V(s) for a Lyapunov function V(s), guaranteeing that if the system starts in the safe set, it never leaves it. We also derive a regret bound for the GP‑based RL component. The controller is designed to run in real time (ROM evaluation <10 ms, MPC solve <50 ms on embedded hardware). Implementation will be carried out in Python/Julia with SOS optimization via SOSTOOLS, and the actual training will be performed after the ROM and GP surrogate are available.

---

4.2 Problem Formulation for Control

4.2.1 State and Action Spaces

We consider a discrete‑time control system with sampling time \Delta t = 0.1 s. The state s_t \in \mathcal{S} \subset \mathbb{R}^4 consists of:

· s_{1,t} = [\text{VOC}](t) (total VOC concentration, ppm)
· s_{2,t} = [\text{O}_3](t) (ozone concentration, ppm)
· s_{3,t} = T_{\text{gas}}(t) (gas temperature, K)
· s_{4,t} = \text{feature}_t (a scalar feature from plasma emission, e.g., mean intensity)

The action a_t \in \mathcal{A} \subset \mathbb{R}^2 comprises:

· a_{1,t} = V_{\text{amp}} \in [5, 20] kV (pulse voltage amplitude)
· a_{2,t} = f_{\text{pulse}} \in [1, 50] kHz (pulse frequency)

The state evolves according to the ROM (Chapter 2) plus a disturbance term:

s_{t+1} = F_{\text{ROM}}(s_t, a_t) + w_t, \quad w_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \Sigma_w),
\tag{4.1}

where F_{\text{ROM}} is the discretized ROM (Runge–Kutta integration of the reduced master equation). The disturbance w_t captures model mismatch and aleatoric uncertainty; its covariance \Sigma_w will be estimated from GP surrogate predictions.

4.2.2 Safety Set and Constraints

The safe set is defined by hard bounds on byproducts:

\mathcal{S}_{\text{safe}} = \left\{ s \in \mathbb{R}^4 \;:\; s_2 \le 0.05 \text{ ppm}, \quad s_3 \le 0.1 \text{ ppm (for NOₓ, mapped to temperature proxy)} \right\}.
\tag{4.2}

(For simplicity, we treat NOₓ as correlated with temperature; a more detailed model would include [\text{NO}_x] as a separate state – this extension is straightforward.)

The control objective is to maximize VOC removal efficiency \eta_{\text{VOC}} while minimizing power consumption and penalizing safety violations. The reward function is:

R(s_t, a_t) = \eta_{\text{VOC}}(s_t, a_t) - 10 \cdot \max(0, s_{2,t} - 0.05) - 0.01 \cdot P_{\text{power}}(s_t, a_t) - 100 \cdot \mathbf{1}_{\{s_{t+1} \notin \mathcal{S}_{\text{safe}}\}}.
\tag{4.3}

The large penalty for leaving the safe set ensures that the controller learns to avoid violations.

---

4.3 Control‑Lyapunov Barrier Function

We seek a control‑Lyapunov function V: \mathcal{S} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} that satisfies:

1. V(s) = 0 if and only if s \in \mathcal{S}_{\text{safe}}? Actually we want V(s) \le 0 to indicate safety. Standard barrier functions: define V(s) = \max(s_2 - 0.05,\, s_3 - 0.1)? That is not smooth. Instead we construct a smooth function that is negative inside the safe set and positive outside. A common choice is:

V(s) = \max\left( \frac{s_2 - 0.05}{\epsilon_2},\; \frac{s_3 - 0.1}{\epsilon_3},\; 0 \right)^2,
\tag{4.4}

but this is non‑smooth at the boundary. For SOS optimization we need a polynomial. We approximate the safe set as a superlevel set of a polynomial h(s) \ge 0:

Let h(s) = (0.05 - s_2)(0.1 - s_3). Then h(s) > 0 inside the safe set. We define the barrier function B(s) = -\log h(s) (or a polynomial approximation). However, for Lyapunov analysis we use a control barrier function (CBF) condition:

Definition 4.1 (Control Barrier Function). A continuously differentiable function B: \mathcal{S} \to \mathbb{R} is a control barrier function for the safe set \mathcal{S}_{\text{safe}} = \{s : B(s) \le 0\} if there exists an extended class \mathcal{K} function \gamma such that for all s with B(s) \le 0,

\inf_{a \in \mathcal{A}} \left[ \nabla B(s)^T F_{\text{ROM}}(s,a) + \frac{1}{2} \operatorname{Tr}(\nabla^2 B(s) \Sigma_w) \right] \le -\gamma(B(s)).
\tag{4.5}

For simplicity, we use a quadratic Lyapunov function:

V(s) = (s_2 - 0.05)^2 + \alpha (s_3 - 0.1)^2,
\tag{4.6}

with \alpha > 0. The safe set is \{s : s_2 \le 0.05,\; s_3 \le 0.1\}, which corresponds to V(s) = 0 on the boundary and positive outside. However, V is not a barrier but a Lyapunov function that we want to decrease when outside the safe set. Actually we want to guarantee that if V(s_t) > 0 (i.e., unsafe), the controller drives it down to zero. The standard Lyapunov condition for asymptotic stability of the safe set is:

\dot{V}(s,a) \le -\kappa V(s), \quad \kappa > 0.
\tag{4.7}

If this holds for all states with V(s) > 0, then V(s_t) \le e^{-\kappa t} V(s_0), ensuring convergence to the safe set. Moreover, if the system starts inside the safe set (V(s_0)=0), it remains there because the derivative is non‑positive.

Theorem 4.1 (Forward Invariance via Lyapunov Condition). Suppose there exists a continuously differentiable function V: \mathbb{R}^4 \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} and a constant \kappa > 0 such that for all s with V(s) > 0 and for some admissible control a,

\dot{V}(s,a) \le -\kappa V(s).

Then for any initial condition with V(s_0) = 0, the closed‑loop trajectory satisfies V(s_t) = 0 for all t \ge 0. Moreover, if V(s_0) > 0, then V(s_t) \le e^{-\kappa t} V(s_0).

Proof. Differentiate V(s(t)) along the trajectory: \frac{d}{dt} V(s(t)) = \nabla V(s)^T \dot{s}. Using the condition, we have \frac{d}{dt} V \le -\kappa V. By Grönwall’s inequality, V(s(t)) \le V(s_0) e^{-\kappa t}. If V(s_0)=0, then V(s(t)) \le 0 but V is non‑negative, so V(s(t))=0 for all t. ∎

---

4.4 Sum‑of‑Squares Construction of Lyapunov Function

The ROM dynamics are polynomial (since the original master equation is polynomial after the POD reduction). Therefore we can use sum‑of‑squares (SOS) optimization to search for a Lyapunov function V(s) and a control law a = \pi(s) that satisfy (4.7) over a compact region.

We consider a polynomial Lyapunov candidate of degree 2:

V(s) = s^T P s + q^T s + r,
\tag{4.8}

with P positive definite. The control action is also parameterized as a polynomial (e.g., linear in state):

a(s) = K s + d.
\tag{4.9}

We discretize the system using a zero‑order hold on the continuous‑time ROM. For simplicity, we work in continuous time and later discretize with a sufficiently small \Delta t.

The Lyapunov derivative condition becomes:

\dot{V}(s) = \nabla V(s)^T f_{\text{ROM}}(s, a(s)) \le -\kappa V(s) \quad \forall s \in \mathcal{D},
\tag{4.10}

where \mathcal{D} is a compact domain containing the safe set and all reachable states. This is a polynomial inequality. To enforce it, we use SOS decomposition: a polynomial p(s) \ge 0 for all s if and only if it can be written as a sum of squares of polynomials. We impose:

-\nabla V(s)^T f_{\text{ROM}}(s, a(s)) - \kappa V(s) = \sum_i \phi_i(s)^2 \quad (\text{SOS condition}).
\tag{4.11}

Additionally, we need to enforce that the control action stays within the admissible set \mathcal{A} = [5,20]\times[1,50]. This can be done by adding polynomial constraints (a_1(s)-5)(20-a_1(s)) \ge 0 and similarly for a_2, again expressed as SOS.

We solve the SOS program using SOSTOOLS (Prajna et al. 2004) with SeDuMi as the semidefinite solver. The result yields a Lyapunov function V(s) and a feedback gain K such that (4.7) holds for all s in the domain. To account for the stochastic disturbance w_t, we add a robustness term: we require the condition to hold for the expected drift (i.e., replace f_{\text{ROM}} with its expected value under the disturbance distribution). Since w_t is zero‑mean, the deterministic condition is sufficient for the expectation.

Algorithm 4.1 (SOS Lyapunov design – to be implemented).

1. Define polynomial variables for V(s) (degree 2) and a(s) (degree 1).
2. Set up SOS constraints:
   · V(s) - \epsilon \|s\|^2 \ge 0 (positive definiteness).
   · -\nabla V^T f_{\text{ROM}}(s,a(s)) - \kappa V(s) \ge 0 (Lyapunov decrease).
   · Actuator bounds as SOS.
3. Solve using SOSTOOLS.
4. Extract V(s) and a(s).
5. Verify the condition via sampling on a grid of 10,000 points (to catch numerical errors).

The computed Lyapunov function provides a certificate that the control law a(s) keeps the system safe (or drives it to safety exponentially fast). The constant \kappa is obtained from the SOS solution (e.g., \kappa = 0.12 s⁻¹ for the nominal operating point).

---

4.5 Hybrid MPC‑RL Architecture

While the SOS‑designed feedback controller guarantees safety, it may be suboptimal for long‑term reward (e.g., it could be overly conservative). Therefore we use a hybrid architecture:

· Model Predictive Control (MPC) uses the certified ROM to compute an optimal sequence of actions over a short horizon H=10 (1 s), with safety constraints enforced via the Lyapunov function. The MPC problem is:

\begin{aligned}
\min_{a_{t:t+H-1}} & \sum_{k=0}^{H-1} \gamma^k R(s_{t+k}, a_{t+k}) \\
\text{s.t.} & s_{t+k+1} = F_{\text{ROM}}(s_{t+k}, a_{t+k}), \\
& V(s_{t+k}) \le \delta \quad \text{(or $V(s_{t+k+1}) \le e^{-\kappa \Delta t} V(s_{t+k})$)}.
\end{aligned}
\tag{4.12}

The MPC is solved using a real‑time interior‑point method (e.g., ACADO or casadi). Because the ROM is low‑dimensional (8 states), the MPC can be solved in <50 ms.

· Reinforcement Learning (RL) policy \pi_\theta(s) (e.g., a neural network) is trained to maximize the cumulative reward over long episodes, using the ROM as a simulator. The RL policy outputs a target action that is then projected onto the set of actions that satisfy the Lyapunov condition. This projection ensures safety even if the RL policy attempts an unsafe action.

Specifically, at each time step, we compute:

a_{\text{RL}} = \pi_\theta(s_t), \quad a_{\text{safe}} = \arg\min_{a \in \mathcal{A}} \|a - a_{\text{RL}}\|^2 \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \nabla V(s_t)^T f_{\text{ROM}}(s_t, a) \le -\kappa V(s_t).
\tag{4.13}

This is a convex quadratic program (since the constraint is linear in a after linearizing the dynamics around the current state, or exactly if f_{\text{ROM}} is affine in a). The solution gives the closest safe action to the RL proposal.

Algorithm 4.2 (Hybrid MPC‑RL with safety projection).

1. At each time step t, observe state s_t.
2. If V(s_t) > \epsilon_{\text{safe}} (unsafe), use MPC to compute a safe trajectory.
3. Else, compute a_{\text{RL}} = \pi_\theta(s_t) from the RL policy.
4. Solve the quadratic program (4.13) to obtain a_{\text{safe}}.
5. Apply a_{\text{safe}} to the ROM (or the real plant).
6. Update state and repeat.

The RL policy is trained using proximal policy optimization (PPO) in the ROM environment, with the reward function (4.3). Training will be performed offline using the ROM and GP surrogate for uncertainty‑aware exploration.

