Chapter 5: Bayesian Optimization for Reactor Design under Stochastic Constraints

5.1 Introduction

The design of the plasma reactor itself – electrode geometry, dielectric thickness, catalyst loading, catalyst type, and packing density – determines the achievable VOC removal efficiency, power consumption, and lifetime. Traditional design optimization relies on exhaustive parameter sweeps or heuristic rules, which are inefficient and do not provide convergence guarantees. Moreover, design constraints such as flow uniformity across the catalyst bed are stochastic due to manufacturing tolerances and random packing.

In this chapter we develop a Bayesian optimization (BO) framework that:

· Uses a Gaussian process surrogate (Chapter 3) to model the design‑to‑performance map.
· Incorporates stochastic constraints via a GP on the constraint function (e.g., flow uniformity), with a safe set defined by a probability threshold.
· Provides convergence guarantees (simple regret O(\sqrt{\gamma_T/T})) using the SAFE‑BO algorithm (Grimm et al. 2024).
· Handles mixed continuous and categorical design variables.
· Includes a multi‑fidelity extension to combine low‑fidelity ROM simulations with high‑fidelity CFD‑plasma simulations for accelerated lifetime prediction.

The output is an optimal reactor design x^* (vector of geometric and material parameters) with a certified performance and a lifetime >10,000 h. The optimization will be performed offline using the ROM and GP surrogate; no physical experiments are required.

---

5.2 Problem Formulation for Design Optimization

5.2.1 Design Variables

The design vector x \in \mathcal{X} \subset \mathbb{R}^5 consists of:

· x_1 = \text{gap\_distance} \in [2, 8] mm (electrode gap)
· x_2 = \text{dielectric\_thickness} \in [0.5, 3] mm (quartz dielectric)
· x_3 = \text{catalyst\_loading} \in [0, 20] wt% (MnO₂ on γ‑Al₂O₃)
· x_4 = \text{catalyst\_type} \in \{0,1\} (0 = MnO₂, 1 = LaCoO₃)
· x_5 = \text{packing\_density} \in [0.2, 0.8] (void fraction)

The first three are continuous, the fourth is binary (categorical), and the fifth is continuous.

5.2.2 Performance Objectives

We aim to minimize a weighted combination of power consumption and byproduct formation while maximizing VOC removal. We define the objective function f(x) as the negative of the reward (so we minimize f):

f(x) = -\left( \eta_{\text{VOC}}(x) - c_1 \cdot [\text{O}_3](x) - c_2 \cdot P_{\text{power}}(x) \right),
\tag{5.1}

with c_1 = 10 (penalty for ozone), c_2 = 0.01. The quantities \eta_{\text{VOC}}, [\text{O}_3], P_{\text{power}} are evaluated by running the ROM (or the GP surrogate) at the nominal operating point (E/N=200 Td, \tau=0.1 s, [\text{VOC}]_0=2 ppm).

5.2.3 Stochastic Constraint

The flow uniformity across the catalyst bed must be at least 0.95 (dimensionless). However, due to random packing and manufacturing variability, the uniformity u(x) is a random variable. We model u(x) as a GP:

u(x) \sim \mathcal{GP}\bigl(\mu_u(x), k_u(x,x')\bigr),
\tag{5.2}

where the mean and kernel are learned from CFD simulations (literature data). The safety constraint is probabilistic:

P\bigl(u(x) \ge 0.95\bigr) \ge 0.9.
\tag{5.3}

We define the safe set \mathcal{X}_{\text{safe}} = \{ x \in \mathcal{X} : P(u(x) \ge 0.95) \ge 0.9 \}.

---

5.3 Bayesian Optimization with Stochastic Constraints (SAFE‑BO)

We adopt the SAFE‑BO algorithm (Grimm et al. 2024), which alternates between learning the objective and the constraint GP, and uses an acquisition function that only queries points that are likely safe.

5.3.1 Gaussian Process Models

We place independent GP priors on the objective f(x) and the constraint u(x) (or on a transformation thereof). For the constraint, we model the probability of feasibility directly. Let z(x) = \mathbf{1}\{u(x) \ge 0.95\}. Then z(x) is a Bernoulli random variable with success probability p(x) = P(u(x) \ge 0.95). We can model p(x) using a classification GP (probit or logistic link). Alternatively, we model u(x) as a GP and compute p(x) = \Phi\bigl((0.95 - \mu_u(x))/\sigma_u(x)\bigr), where \Phi is the standard normal CDF. We adopt the latter because it directly uses the GP predictive distribution.

5.3.2 Acquisition Function

The acquisition function for SAFE‑BO is the Expected Improvement with safety constraint:

\alpha_{\text{SAFE}}(x) = \text{EI}(x) \cdot \mathbf{1}\bigl\{ p(x) \ge 0.9 \bigr\},
\tag{5.4}

where \text{EI}(x) = \mathbb{E}[\max(0, f(x_{\text{best}}) - f(x))] is the standard expected improvement. The indicator ensures that we only evaluate points that are predicted to be safe with at least 90% probability.

In practice, we replace the hard indicator with a continuous relaxation: \alpha_{\text{SAFE}}(x) = \text{EI}(x) \cdot \Phi\bigl((p(x)-0.9)/\sigma_p\bigr) to avoid zero gradients.

Algorithm 5.1 (SAFE‑BO – to be implemented).

1. Initialize: sample n_0 = 20 points using Latin hypercube design; evaluate f(x) and u(x) (via ROM and CFD surrogate).
2. Fit GP models for f and u.
3. For t = 1 to T = 200:
      a. Compute \alpha_{\text{SAFE}}(x) on a candidate set of 10,000 random points.
      b. Select x_{t+1} = \arg\max \alpha_{\text{SAFE}}(x).
      c. Evaluate f(x_{t+1}) and u(x_{t+1}) (using ROM and CFD surrogate).
      d. Update the GP models.
4. Return the best feasible point x^* = \arg\min_{x \in \text{safe}} f(x).

---

5.4 Convergence Guarantees

Theorem 5.1 (Simple regret bound for SAFE‑BO). Under the assumptions that:

· The objective f and constraint u lie in the RKHS of their respective Matérn‑7/2 kernels with bounded norm.
· The safe set \mathcal{X}_{\text{safe}} is non‑empty and has positive volume.
· The acquisition function satisfies a Lipschitz condition.

Then after T evaluations, the simple regret R_T = f(x^*) - \min_{x \in \mathcal{X}_{\text{safe}}} f(x) satisfies:

R_T = O\left( \sqrt{\frac{\gamma_T}{T}} \right),
\tag{5.5}

with high probability, where \gamma_T is the maximum information gain for the joint GP (which scales as O(T^{5/12} \log T) for 5 dimensions).

Proof sketch. The result follows from the standard regret bound for GP‑UCB (Srinivas et al. 2010) extended to the constrained case. The safety constraint reduces the feasible region, but the acquisition function only queries points with p(x) \ge 0.9, which, after enough samples, includes the true optimum with high probability. The contraction rate of the GP posterior ensures that the simple regret decays at the same rate as in the unconstrained case, up to a constant factor. For a detailed proof, see Grimm et al. (2024, Theorem 3.1). ∎

Corollary 5.1 (Lifetime certification). After obtaining the optimal design x^*, we run a multi‑fidelity simulation (low‑fidelity: 0D ROM; high‑fidelity: CFD‑plasma) to predict the deactivation rate d(\text{deactivation})/dt = g(x^*, T, [\text{CO}], \text{dust}). Using the GP surrogate for g, we compute the 95% credible interval for the lifetime. We require the lower bound to exceed 10,000 h. If not, we perform additional BO iterations focused on maximizing lifetime.

---

5.5 Multi‑Fidelity Bayesian Optimization

To reduce computational cost, we use a multi‑fidelity approach:

· Low fidelity: ROM (0D master equation, 10 ms per evaluation) – cheap but less accurate.
· High fidelity: CFD‑plasma simulation (2 hours per evaluation) – expensive but accurate.

We use the multi‑fidelity GP (MF‑GP) of Kennedy & O’Hagan (2000), which models the low‑fidelity function f_{\text{low}}(x) and the discrepancy d(x) = f_{\text{high}}(x) - f_{\text{low}}(x). The acquisition function is then optimized on the high‑fidelity prediction. This reduces the number of expensive high‑fidelity evaluations from 200 to about 20.

Algorithm 5.2 (Multi‑fidelity SAFE‑BO).

1. Evaluate 200 low‑fidelity points (ROM) to train f_{\text{low}} and u_{\text{low}}.
2. Select 20 high‑fidelity points using the acquisition function that balances exploration and exploitation.
3. Run CFD simulations for those 20 points.
4. Train the discrepancy GP and update the high‑fidelity surrogate.
5. Perform final optimization on the high‑fidelity surrogate.

---

5.6 Implementation Plan

We will implement SAFE‑BO in Python using:

· GPyTorch for GP regression and classification.
· BoTorch for acquisition functions and optimization.
· CFD surrogate: We will not run CFD ourselves; instead we will use published data (e.g., from literature on packed bed flow uniformity) to train the constraint GP. This is a mathematical design; the actual CFD data will be taken from existing studies (e.g., Grimm et al. 2024).

The code will be structured as follows:

```python
# safe_bo.py
import botorch
from botorch.models import SingleTaskGP
from botorch.acquisition import ExpectedImprovement
from botorch.optim import optimize_acqf

def safe_acquisition(model_f, model_u, X_candidates, threshold=0.9):
    # Compute predictive mean and variance for u
    mu_u, sigma_u = model_u.posterior(X_candidates).mean, model_u.posterior(X_candidates).variance.sqrt()
    p_safe = torch.distributions.Normal(mu_u, sigma_u).cdf(torch.tensor(0.95))
    # Compute EI for f
    ei = ExpectedImprovement(model_f, best_f=model_f.best)
    alpha = ei(X_candidates) * (p_safe >= threshold).float()
    return alpha

# Main loop
for t in range(T):
    candidates = generate_random_points(10000)
    acq_val = safe_acquisition(model_f, model_u, candidates)
    x_new = candidates[acq_val.argmax()]
    y_f_new = evaluate_rom(x_new)   # or high-fidelity
    y_u_new = evaluate_uniformity_cfd_surrogate(x_new)
    update_models(x_new, y_f_new, y_u_new)
```

The final output is the optimal design vector x^* and a certification report (including the GP predictive intervals for lifetime). The code will be released at github.com/ouadimaakoul/plasma_bo.

