7.2 Validation of the Certified ROM

7.2.1 Comparison with Literature Data

Kozák et al. (2021) published experimental data for CO₂ conversion in a low‑pressure pulsed DC discharge at pressures of 1000, 2000, 5000 Pa. We will simulate their exact conditions using our ROM (with the Knudsen correction disabled for those pressures, since \text{Kn}_e < 0.1). The ROM output (CO conversion fraction, electron density) will be compared to the experimental measurements.

Success criterion: RMSE < 10% for CO conversion across all pressure points.

To extrapolate to 600 Pa, we will run the ROM with the Knudsen correction (\alpha = 0.35) and compare with scaling laws from the literature. The error bound from Theorem 2.2 ensures that the ROM’s error relative to the true physics (if it were known) is ≤5% for 600 Pa.

7.2.2 POD Error Bound Verification

After generating the ensemble of 2000 simulations, we will compute the POD singular values and verify that \sqrt{\sum_{i=9}^{35} \sigma_i^2} / \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{35} \sigma_i^2} \le 0.01. Then, we will select 500 validation parameter sets (not used in the ensemble) and compare the ROM output (with r=8) to the full high‑fidelity solution. The relative L_2 error will be computed at each time step.

Success criterion: 95% of the validation points have maximum relative error <5%.

---

7.3 Validation of GP Surrogate

7.3.1 Coverage of Credible Intervals

We will generate 10,000 test points x_{\text{test}} uniformly in the input domain. For each point, we compute the ROM output y_{\text{true}} and the GP predictive mean \hat{\mu}(x) and 95% credible interval [\hat{\mu} - 1.96\hat{\sigma},\; \hat{\mu} + 1.96\hat{\sigma}]. The empirical coverage is the fraction of points where y_{\text{true}} lies inside the interval.

Success criterion: Empirical coverage ≥ 90% for each output dimension.

7.3.2 Active Learning Efficiency

We will run the active learning algorithm (Algorithm 3.2) for 200 iterations, starting from 50 initial points. We will track the maximum predictive standard deviation for ozone as a function of iterations. A reduction of at least 80% from the initial value is expected.

---

7.4 Validation of Safe RL Controller

7.4.1 Safety Constraint Satisfaction

We will simulate the closed‑loop system (ROM + hybrid MPC‑RL controller) for 1000 random VOC load transients (step from 1 ppm to 10 ppm at random times). We will record the number of times the ozone concentration exceeds 0.05 ppm.

Success criterion: No violation occurs in any simulation (i.e., 0% violation rate). If the Lyapunov condition holds exactly, this is guaranteed by Theorem 4.1. Numerical errors may cause rare violations; we accept ≤1% violation rate.

7.4.2 Reward Convergence

We will train the RL policy (PPO) on the ROM environment for 1 million time steps. The cumulative reward per episode should converge to a stable value. We will compare the converged reward against a baseline PID controller tuned for the same task.

Success criterion: RL policy achieves at least 20% higher reward than the best tuned PID.

