8.3 Path to Hardware Integration

The mathematical framework and open‑source libraries provided in this thesis are designed for straightforward integration with physical hardware. The following steps would be required for a future experimental campaign:

1. Replace the ROM with real‑time sensor data – The control loop uses the same API; the RL controller only requires state estimates (VOC, O₃, temperature, emission feature). These can be obtained from FTIR, UV ozone analyzer, thermocouples, and a photodiode.
2. Calibrate the GP surrogate – The GP hyperparameters can be updated online using Bayesian inference from incoming data.
3. Run the RL policy on an embedded computer – The policy is a small neural network (few hundred parameters) that can run on a Raspberry Pi or NVIDIA Jetson.
4. Use the CV system with a real camera – The CNN was trained on synthetic scalograms; fine‑tuning with a few hundred real images would adapt it to the actual camera.

Our code is modular and well‑documented to facilitate this transition. The lead institution (Mathematics Department) will collaborate with JPL/ESTEC to perform hardware integration in a follow‑up project.

