8.4 Limitations and Future Work

While this thesis provides rigorous mathematical foundations, several limitations remain:

· The Knudsen correction (\alpha = 0.35) was calibrated from PIC simulations in the literature. A more fundamental derivation from the full Boltzmann equation would improve confidence.
· The ROM assumes spatial homogeneity (0‑D). For larger reactors or lower pressures, 1‑D or 2‑D effects may become important. The POD method can be extended to include spatial modes.
· The GP surrogate uses a stationary kernel; non‑stationary behavior (e.g., near the safety boundary) might require input warping or deep GPs.
· The RL policy was trained on the ROM; transfer to the real plant may require domain randomization or robust control techniques.
· The CNN was trained on synthetic data; real‑world images may exhibit different noise characteristics. Active learning with real data would be needed.

Future work includes:

· Extending the ROM to 1‑D (radial profile) using POD on a spatial‑temporal ensemble.
· Developing a robust MPC that accounts for GP uncertainty directly (e.g., using chance constraints).
· Implementing the entire framework on an FPGA for microsecond‑level control.
· Validating the system on a physical DBD reactor at 600 Pa in collaboration with a plasma physics lab.

