8.5 Final Remarks

This thesis has demonstrated that rigorous mathematics—existence/uniqueness proofs, certified reduced‑order modeling, uncertainty quantification, Lyapunov stability, and Bayesian optimization—can be applied to a real‑world aerospace problem: trace VOC oxidation in Martian habitats. The result is not just an empirical device but a mathematically certified system that meets NASA/ESA safety and performance standards.

Without this foundation, plasma‑catalytic life support remains an empirical art. With it, we enable closed‑loop air revitalization that is provably safe, efficient, and robust—a critical step toward sustainable human presence on Mars.

All code and proofs are open‑source. We invite the community to use, test, and extend this framework.

